# Purpose

Procedure for evolving MongoDB collection schemas and data without a formal migration tool.

# Rules

- MongoDB is schema-less. There is NO migration tooling (no Prisma Migrate, no Mongoose migrations).
- Schema changes are applied by updating the Zod document schemas and repository logic.
- DO NOT drop or rename collections without explicit intent and a data migration plan.
- DO NOT apply destructive changes to production without a backup.

# Workflow

## 1. Update the Zod Document Schema

In `backend/src/aop/db/mongo/repository/<collection>/schemas/`:

- Add, remove, or modify fields in the document schema.
- Use `.optional()` or `.nullable()` for new fields to maintain backward compatibility with existing documents.

```typescript
// Adding a nullable field safely
export const jobDocumentSchema = z.object({
    _id: z.instanceof(ObjectId),
    userId: z.string(),
    name: z.string(),
    newField: z.string().nullable(), // new — existing docs will have null
});
```

## 2. Update Types

Rederive the TypeScript type from the updated schema:

```typescript
export type JobDocument = z.infer<typeof jobDocumentSchema>;
```

## 3. Update Repository Methods

If new fields affect queries, update the repository methods in `repository/<collection>/index.ts`.

## 4. Backfill Existing Documents (if required)

If existing documents need the new field populated, write a one-off script:

```typescript
// backend/scripts/backfill-<description>.ts
import { MongoClient } from 'mongodb';
// Connect, query, update, disconnect
```

Run manually: `ts-node -r tsconfig-paths/register scripts/backfill-<description>.ts`

DO NOT run backfill scripts in production without verifying on a staging instance first.

## 5. Update Index (if new unique/query field)

Add the index directly in the MongoDB startup or via the repository context setup in `aop/db/mongo`.

## Validation Commands

```bash
cd backend && npm run type-check
cd backend && npm run test:integration
```

## Completion Criteria

- [ ] Zod document schema updated with backward-compatible field types
- [ ] TypeScript types rederived from schemas
- [ ] Repository methods updated if query logic changed
- [ ] Backfill script written and reviewed if existing documents need updating
- [ ] `npm run type-check` passes
- [ ] Integration tests pass against updated schema
